e them pass\"; \"fix bug\" → \"reproduce with a failing test, then make it pass\".\n- For multi-step work, write a brief plan with a per-step verification check before executing, so you can loop independently instead of asking for confirmation each step.\n- Every changed line should trace back to the task. If it doesn't, drop it.\n\n## CLI tools\n\nPrefer the Nix-managed tools below over slower or less precise defaults when they fit the task.\n\n| tool             | replaces                        | usage                                                                               |\n|------------------|---------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| `rg` (`ripgrep`) | `grep`                          | `rg \"pattern\"` - fast recursive text search                                         |\n| `fd`             | `find`                          | `fd -g \"*.nix\"` - fast file finder with sensible defaults                           |\n| `ast-grep`       | text-only code search           | `ast-grep run --pattern '$FUNC($$$)' --lang php src/` - AST-aware structural search |\n| `actionlint`     | ad hoc workflow review          | `actionlint` - lint GitHub Actions workflows                                        |\n| `zizmor`         | ad hoc workflow security review | `zizmor .github/workflows/` - audit GitHub Actions security posture                 |\n\nUse `ast-grep` for code patterns (avoids false positives from comments/strings). Fall back to `rg` for plain text, docs, and unsupported languages.\n\n## SCM\n\n- Never use `git reset --hard` or push without explicit permission.\n- If force-pushing is required, use `git push --force-with-lease --force-if-includes` (or just `git push --force-with-lease` if previous one is impossible, analyzing the root cause for fail first, and making sure these changes would not override remote branch updates)\n- Never merge PRs without explicit permission — always ask first, even if CI passes.\n- Prefer safe alternatives (`git revert`, new commits, temp branches).\n- If history rewrite seems necessary, explain and ask first.\n- Add `Co-Authored-By: chatgpt-codex-connector[bot] <199175422+chatgpt-codex-connector[bot]@users.noreply.github.com>` to commits by default, unless explicitly asked not to.\n\n## Using GitHub\n\nFor questions about GitHub, use the `gh` tool and `/octocat` skill.\nAlways run `gh` commands with escalated permissions; sandboxed `gh` calls fail in this environment because network access is restricted there.\nNever mention Codex in PR descriptions, PR comments, or issue comments unless asked explicitly.\nDo not include a \"Test plan\" section in PR descriptions.\n\n## Coding Standards\n\n### PHP Coding Standards\n\nWhen working with Laravel/PHP projects, always use the `php-guidelines-from-spatie` skill.\n\n## Reviewing external feedback\n\n- ALWAYS load the `superpowers:receiving-code-review` skill upon receiving review feedback (PR comments, agent reviews). The skill enforces technical rigor and verification over performative agreement.\n- When acting on PR review comments (from bots or humans), independently verify factual claims before applying fixes — especially version numbers, library existence, API behavior, and deprecation status.\n- If a claim falls outside your knowledge cutoff, use WebSearch or check local evidence (installed packages, lock files, docker images) before trusting it.\n- Use `pr-review-fetcher` agent to fetch Pull Review reviews and comments.\n\n## Production safety\n\n- Assume production impact unless stated otherwise.\n- Call out risk when touching auth, billing, data, APIs, or build systems.\n- Prefer small, reversible changes; avoid silent breaking behavior.\n\n## Self improvement\n\n- Continuously improve agent workflows.\n- When a repeated correction or better approach is found you're encouraged to codify your new found knowledge and learnings by modifying your section of